<h2>South Dakota Incentives & Rebates</h2>
<p>South Dakota homeowners have access to several valuable incentive programs that significantly reduce the cost of solar and HVAC installations. The most substantial incentive is the federal solar Investment Tax Credit (ITC), which provides a 30% tax credit for solar panel installations completed through 2032. This credit applies to the total system cost, including equipment, installation, and related expenses like electrical upgrades and permits.</p>

<ul>
<li><strong>Federal 30% Solar Tax Credit:</strong> Available for solar installations through 2032, then stepping down to 26% in 2033 and 22% in 2034. The credit can be carried forward to future tax years if it exceeds current tax liability, and there's no maximum limit on the credit amount.</li>
<li><strong>Property Tax Exemption:</strong> South Dakota exempts solar energy systems from property tax assessments, meaning the added home value from solar installation won't increase property taxes. This exemption can save hundreds of dollars annually for typical residential systems.</li>
<li><strong>Xcel Energy Solar Rewards:</strong> Xcel Energy offers production-based incentives for solar installations, currently providing credits for solar energy production over 20-year terms. The program includes simplified interconnection processes and guaranteed net metering credits.</li>
<li><strong>Rural Energy for America Program (REAP):</strong> Available through USDA for rural properties, offering grants up to 25% of project costs and low-interest loans for renewable energy systems, including solar and geothermal installations.</li>
<li><strong>HVAC Rebates:</strong> Various utility companies offer rebates for high-efficiency HVAC equipment, typically ranging from \$200-800 for heat pumps, \$100-400 for high-efficiency furnaces, and up to \$1,200 for geothermal systems through federal and state programs.</li>
</ul>

